Collaborative To-Do List Application

## Project Overview
Name: Collaborative To-Do List Web Application
Description: A web-based task management system that allows users to create workspaces, collaborate on tasks, and track project progress in real-time using MongoDB.
Goal: To solve productivity management issues in groups or teams by providing structured task assignments and flexible NoSQL data storage.
Target Users: University students, developers, and small project teams.
Version: v1.0.0
Status: Active Development

## Tech Stack
Language: JavaScript (Node.js)
Framework: Express.js
Styling: Tailwind CSS
UI Library: None (Custom HTML/CSS with Tailwind)
Database: MongoDB
ORM: Mongoose
Auth: JWT (JSON Web Tokens) & bcrypt
State Management: None (Server-rendered / Vanilla JS)
Data Fetching: Axios / Fetch API
Package Manager: npm
Deployment: Localhost (Development)

## Commands
# Development
npm run dev          # Run development server with nodemon
npm start            # Run production build server
# Package Management
npm install [package] # Install new dependency package
# Testing
npm run test         # Run all tests
# Database
npm run db:seed      # Seed initial template data to MongoDB

## Project Structure
Architecture: By Feature (Screaming Architecture)

[root]/
├── config/
│   └── db.js                 # Shared Mongoose database connection initialization
├── src/
│   ├── features/             # Core business features
│   │   ├── auth/             # Authentication feature module
│   │   │   ├── authController.js
│   │   │   ├── authRoutes.js
│   │   │   ├── authModel.js       # Mongoose Schema for Users
│   │   │   └── authValidator.js   # Server-side data validation for user signup/login
│   │   │
│   │   ├── workspaces/       # Workspace (Collaboration space) feature module
│   │   │   ├── workspaceController.js
│   │   │   ├── workspaceRoutes.js
│   │   │   └── workspaceModel.js  # Mongoose Schema for Workspaces
│   │   │
│   │   └── tasks/            # Tasks management feature module (CRUD + Search & Filter)
│   │       ├── taskController.js
│   │       ├── taskRoutes.js
│   │       ├── taskModel.js       # Mongoose Schema for Tasks
│   │       └── taskValidator.js
│   │
│   ├── middlewares/          # Shared global cross-cutting concerns middlewares
│   │   ├── authMiddleware.js      # Formulates session verification and role checks (admin vs user)
│   │   └── errorMiddleware.js     # Centralized uniform error management
│   │
│   └── app.js                # Initiates Express instance and registers global modules
├── public/                   # Static assets accessible by public
├── .env                      # Local secret variables configuration (Git ignored)
├── .gitignore                # Tells Git what to ignore (node_modules, .env)
├── package.json              # Project dependencies manifest file
└── server.js                 # Application network boundary setup entrypoint

# File Placement Rules:
- UI Components are placed in public/ or served via views if using template engines.
- Business logic always resides inside `src/features/[feature-name]/`.
- Database query logic must be kept inside controllers or models within their respective feature folder.
- Do not create new folders without prior confirmation.

## Naming Conventions
# File and Folder
Components: PascalCase (if any, e.g., TaskCard.js)
Non-components: camelCase (e.g., authController.js, taskRoutes.js)
Folder: kebab-case (e.g., workspaces/, user-profile/)
Pages: index.html or dashboard.html
Layout: layout.html
Test file: [name].test.js
Variables: camelCase (e.g., userData, isLoading)
Constants: UPPER_SNAKE (e.g., JWT_SECRET, PORT)
Functions: camelCase (e.g., getUserById, formatTaskDate)
Types/Interfaces: PascalCase (if using TypeScript, otherwise Mongoose models use PascalCase: User, Task)
Enum: PascalCase (e.g., UserRole, TaskStatus)
CSS Class: kebab-case (e.g., btn-primary, nav-item)
# Git Branch
Fitur baru: feat/[nama-fitur]
Bug fix: fix/[nama-bug]
Hotfix: hotfix/[nama]
Refactor: refactor/[nama]

## Code Conventions
- Enforce clean code practices, DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself), and Separation of Concerns.
- Avoid code duplication; extract logic into helper functions if used more than once.
- Write readable, descriptive code rather than overly short/clever code.
# Error Handling
- Always use try-catch blocks for async functions and database operations.
- Never leave errors unhandled; log them and pass to next() for centralized handling.
- Write informative and specific error messages.
# Import Sequence
1. External libraries (express, mongoose, etc.)
2. Internal absolute / feature models
3. Internal relative modules (./utils, ../middlewares)
4. Assets and styles
# Export Pattern
- Use named exports for utilities and helper functions.
- Use default export for main modules/routers if required by architecture.

## Component Rules
# Writing Order in One Component
1. Imports
2. Configuration / Constants
3. Main Function / Controller definition
4. Helper functions / local handlers
5. Module Export
# Props Rules
- Explicitly validate object properties passed into functions.
- Use default values for optional parameters.

## Styling Rules
# Styling Approach
- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes directly in HTML/views.
- Do not use inline styles unless for truly dynamic calculated values.
- Do not use !important.
# Responsive Design
- Mobile-first approach.
- Breakpoints: sm (640px) / md (768px) / lg (1024px) / xl (1280px).
# Dark Mode
- Use Tailwind's dark: prefix.
- Always test layout in dark mode after creating new views.
# Design Tokens
- Use standard Tailwind config variables for spacing, colors, and typography.
- Do not hardcode custom hex color values directly in HTML.

## API & Data Fetching Rules
# When to Use Server vs Client Fetch
Server fetch: Fetching core data during template rendering (initial page load).
Client fetch: Dynamic updates after user interactions (filtering, searching, status toggles).
# API Response Format
- Always return a consistent format across all API endpoints:
  `{ "success": boolean, "data": T | null, "message": string }`
# Error Handling in API
- Always handle errors with try-catch blocks.
- Return appropriate HTTP status codes (200, 201, 400, 401, 403, 404, 500).
- Do not expose raw internal database error details to the client in production.
# Fetch Function Location
- Keep all client-side fetch requests or API routing handlers isolated within feature controllers.
# Environment
- Use environment variables for all sensitive database URIs, API keys, and secret tokens.
- Never hardcode credentials directly in code.

## State Management Rules
# State Hierarchy
1. Local state variables for isolated page components.
2. Shared context via global window objects or sessionStorage if multi-page state persistence is needed.
# When to Use Global State
- Storing active user session data or auth tokens needed across multiple features.
- Dynamic global UI components (e.g., global notification banner, sidebar toggle).
- Feature store domain separation: create state boundaries per feature module.

## Performance Rules
# Code Splitting
- Lazy load asset-heavy modules or large third-party libraries only when required.
# Image Optimization
- Always define width and height attributes for layout elements.
- Use WebP or modern image formats for newly added assets.
- Avoid serving uncompressed raw images.
# Re-render Optimization
- Optimize front-end DOM manipulation by avoiding unnecessary complete page redraws; update specific nodes dynamically.
# Bundle Size
- Import only required sub-modules from large npm packages (e.g., import specific methods from lodash instead of the whole library).

## Git Rules
# MANDATORY: Commit After Every Change
- Every time a functional change or feature addition is completed, immediately commit to GitHub before moving to the next task.
- This allows clean rollbacks and easy comparison if results do not meet expectations.
# Format Commit Message
- feat: [description of new feature]
- fix: [description of fixed bug]
- refactor: [description of code refactor]
- style: [changes to code styling or formatting]
- docs: [changes to documentation]
- chore: [changes to configuration or tools]
# Example of a Correct Commit Message
- feat: add user authentication with JWT and bcrypt
- fix: resolve task filtering not resetting on mobile view
- refactor: extract database connection into unified pool config
# addition Rules
- Never commit .env files or files containing secrets.
- One commit per specific change. Do not bundle unrelated changes together.

