## Testing
# Testing Approach
Jenis testing: Manual Testing & Integration Testing
Framework: Jest (if implemented later)
# What Needs to be Tested
- Helper and validator functions.
- Complex business logical paths (e.g., collaborator access authorization).
- API Endpoints (Happy path and error use cases).
# What Not to Test
- Simple presentational UI files.
- Third-party packages (e.g., Mongoose core behavior).
- Configuration files.
# Test Writing Rules
- One test file per source file ([name].test.js).
- Use descriptive naming convention: 'should [expected behavior] when [condition]'.
- Follow AAA pattern: Arrange, Act, Assert.

## Do Not
- If instructions or prompts are ambiguous, ASK FIRST before writing code. Do not assume.
- DO NOT create new folders without explicit confirmation.
- DO NOT delete or move files without permission.
- DO NOT alter the established project structural pattern.
- DO NOT accept un-sanitized user inputs directly into MongoDB queries (prevent NoSQL Injection).
- DO NOT hardcode values meant to come from environment variables.
- DO NOT commit `.env` or configuration secrets.
- DO NOT install new npm packages without confirmation.
- DO NOT bypass validation constraints on API routes.

## Environment Variables
# Setup
- Copy `.env.example` to `.env` for local development.
- Never commit `.env` files to the repository.
# Server-only Variables (Never expose to the client)
PORT=5000                     # Listening port for application server execution
DATABASE_URL=mongodb://...     # Full connection URI string for MongoDB instance
JWT_SECRET=your_secret_key    # Secure string token signature cipher phrase